iIPv4 is currently the most widely supported network protocol, where		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icomputers are identified by IP addresses. Theoretically, it can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iaccommodate up to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork devices (IPv4: 8 hexadecimal digits). Unfortunately, these		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iaddresses have been exhausted, and it's truly a mystery how major ISPs		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iallocate limited IP addresses to an infinite number of computers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIPv6 is far more impressive, with each address containing 32		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihexadecimal digits, allowing for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork devices. These IP addresses will be more than sufficient		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibefore humanity perishes due to Earth's inability to sustain us. This		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprotocol is championed by major internet companies including Google,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDNSPod, and others. However, currently in China, IPv6 seems to be used		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ionly in universities, while ordinary households are limited to IPv4.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Note: Even universities have incomplete implementations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iInternationally, IPv4 and IPv6 are generally supported simultaneously,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibut within China's education network, only IPv6 is available.)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAs IPv6 resources become increasingly abundant, we can leverage		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isoftware solutions to access IPv6 before Chinese ISPs take action.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
